The core idea: feed the hidden state back, don’t decode it
In ordinary autoregressive decoding, the input embedding at each step comes from the previously generated token. Coconut adds a second mode. Special markers &lt;bot&gt; and &lt;eot&gt; (begin/end of thought) bracket a stretch of latent reasoning. Inside that stretch, the input embedding at step \(t\) is not a token embedding — it is the last hidden state from the previous step:
\[
x_t \;=\;
\begin{cases}
\text{Embed}(w_t) & \text{(language mode)}\\[4pt]
h_{t-1} & \text{(latent mode, between }\texttt{&lt;bot&gt;}\text{ and }\texttt{&lt;eot&gt;}\text{)}
\end{cases}
\]
where \(h_{t-1}\) is the final-layer hidden state produced at the previous position. No softmax, no token sampling, no re-embedding — the “continuous thought” is just \(h_{t-1}\) passed forward. After a fixed number of such latent steps, the model emits &lt;eot&gt; and returns to normal language decoding to produce the answer.
The conceptual consequence is the whole point. A decoded token is a single choice; a hidden state is a dense vector that can carry a superposition of possibilities. The authors show, on a graph-reachability planning task, that the continuous thought behaves like the frontier of a breadth-first search: early latent steps keep weight on several candidate next nodes simultaneously, and later steps prune the dead ends. CoT, by contrast, must gamble on one node and hope it can recover if wrong. Reasoning in latent space lets the model defer commitment — it explores in parallel and only collapses to a definite answer when it decodes back to language.
